For to telle ow of his array


His hors were goode but he was not gay


Of fustioun he wered a gepoun


Al bismotered with his haburgoun


For he was late y come from his viage


And wente for to don his pilgrimage


Wi him er was his sone a ong squier


A louyere and a lusty bacheler


Wi lockes crulle as ei were leyd in presse


Of  xx  eer of age he was I gesse


Of his statuture he was of euene lenge


And wonderly deliuere and gret of strenge


An he hadde be somtyme in Chiuachie


In Flaundres in artoys and Pykardie


And born him wel as of so litel space


In hope to stonden in his lady grace


Embroyded was he as it were a mede


A ful of freissche floures white and reede


Synging he was or floytynge al e day


He was als freissch as is e mon of may


Schort was his gowne wi sleeues longe and wyde


Wel coue he sitte on an hors and faire ride


He coue songes make and wel endite


Iuste and eek daunce and wel purteray and write


So hote he loued at by nighter tale


He sleep nomore an do a nightyngale


Courteys he was lowly and seruisable


And karf biforn his fader atte table


A eman hadde he and seruantes namo


At at time for him liste ride so


And he was clad in coote and hood of greene


A scheef of pocok arwes bright and keene


Vnder his belt he bar ful riftily


Wel coude he dresse his takel imanly


His arwes drouped nought wi fetheres lowe


And in his hond he bar a mighty bow




A not hed hadde he wi a broun visage


Of woode craft wel coue he al e vsage


Vpon his arm he bar a gay bracer


And by his syde a swerd and a bocler


And on at oer side a gay daggere


Harnaysed wel and scharp as point of spere


A xpchristophre on his brest of seluer schene


An horn he bar e bawdrik was of grene


A foster was he soly as I gesse


Ther was also a Nonne a Prioresse


That of hir smyling was ful symple a coy


Hir grettest o was but by seint loy


And sche was cleped ma dame Englentyne


Fol wel sche song e seruise diuine


Entuned in hir nose ful semely


And frenssch sche spak ful faire and fetisly


After e scole of stratford atte Bowe


For Frenssh of Parys was to hire vnknowe


At mete wel I taught was sche wi alle


Sche leet no morselle from hire lippes falle


Ne wete hire fyngres in hir sauce deepe


Wel coue sche carie a morsel and wel keepe /


That no drope ne felle vpon hir breste


In Curtesye was sette ful moche hire leste


Hir ouer lippe wyped sche so cleene


That in hir cuppe er was no ferthing seene


Of grete whan sche dronken hadde hir draughte


Ful semely after hir mete sche raughte


And sikerly sche was of gret disporte


And ful plesant and amyable of porte


And peyned hire to counterfete cheere


Of court and to ben estatlich of maneere


And to ben holden digne of reuerence


But for to speken of hir conscience


Sche was so  charitable and so pytous


Sche wolde weepe if at sche sawe a mou




Kaught in a trappe if it were deed or bledde


Of smale houndes hadde sche at sche fedde


With rosted fleissh or mylk or wastel brede


But sore wepte sche if oon of hem were dede


Or if men smot it with a erde smerte /


And al was conscience and tendre herte /


Ful semelich hir wympil pynched was


Hir nose was streight hire yghen grey as glas


Hir mouth ful smal and erto softe and rede


But sikerly sche hadde a fair forhede


It was almost a spanne brood I trowe


For hardely sche was nought vndergrowe


Ful fetys was hir cloke as I was war


Of smal coral aboute hir arm sche bar


A payre of bedes gauded al with greene


And er on heng a broche of gold ful scheene


On which er was first writen with a crowned A .


And after . Amor vincit omnia 


Anoer Nonne with hir hadde sche /


That was hir Chapelleyne and prestes re


A Monk er was a fair for e maistrie


And out Ridere at loued venerie


A manly man to ben an abbot able /


Ful many a deinte hors hadde he in stable /


And whan he rood men might his brydel heere


Gynglyng in a whistlyng wynd as cleere


And eek as lowde as do e chapel belle


Ther as is lord was keper of e selle


The Reule of sent Maure or of seint Beneit


By cause at it was old and somdel streit


This ilke monk leet olde inges pace


And held after e newe world e space


He af nought of e text a pulled hen


That seith at hunters be nought holy men


Ne at a monk whan he is recheles


Is likned til a fyssh at is waterles




This is to seie a monk out of his cloystre


But ilke text / held he not worth an oystre /


And I seide his opinioun was good


What schulde he studie and make himseluen wood


Vpon a book alwey in cloyste to poure


Or swynke with his hondes and laboure


As austyn bit how schal e world be serued


Lat austyn haue his swynk to him reserued


Ther fore he was a prikasour aright


Grehoundes he hadde swift as foule in flight


Of prikynge and of huntyng for e hare


Was alle his luste for no cost wolde he spare


I seigh his sleues I purfiled at e hond


Wi grys and at e fynest of a lond


And for to festne his hood vnder e chynne


He hadde of gold wrought a ful curious pynne /


A loue knotte in e gretter ende er was /


His hed was balled at schon as eny glas


And eek his face as he hadde ben anoynt


He was a lord ful fatt and in good poynt


His eyghen stepe and rollyng in his hede


That stemed as a forneys of a lede


His bootes souple his hors in gret estate


Now certeinly he was a fair prelate


He nas nat pale as a forpyned goost


A fat swan loued he best of any rost


His palfray was as broun as is a berie


A Frere er was a wanton and a merye


A lymitour a ful solempne man


In alle e ordres foure is non at can


So mochil of daliance and fair langage


He hadde made ful many a mariage


Of onge wommen at his owne cost


Vnto his ordre he was a noble post


Ful wel biloued and famulier was he


Wi Frankeleyns ouer al in his contre




And wi wori wommen of e toun


For he hadde power of confessioun


As seyde himself more an a curat


For of his ordre he was licenciat


Ful swetly herde he confessioun


And plesant was his absolucioun


He was an esy man to iue penaunce


Ther as he wiste to haue a good pitaunce


For vnto a pouer ordre for to iue


Is signe at a man is wel I schriue


For if he af he dorste make auant


He wiste at / a man was repentant


For many a man so hard is of his herte


He may nought wepe al ough him sore smerte


Ther fore in stede of weepyng and preyeres


Men mote eue siluer to e pouere freeres


His typet was ay farsed ful of knyfes


And pynnes for to iue faire wyues


And certeynly he hadde a mery note /


Wel coue he synge and playen on a rote


Of eddynges he bar witterly e pris


His nekke whit / was as e flour delys


Ther to he was strong as a Champioun


He knew e tauernes wel in euery toun


And euerich hostiller and tapstere


Bet an a lazar or a Beggere


For vnto such a wori man as he


Acorded nought as by his faculte


To haue with such sek lazer aqueintance


It is nought honest it may nought auaunce


For to delen with such poraile


But alle with Riche and sellere of vitaile


And ouer al er as profyt scholde arise


Curtays he was and lowly of seruise


Ther nas no man nowher so vertuous


He was e beste begger in his hous




For ough a widewe hadde nought a scho


So plesant was his In principio


et wolde he haue a fering or he wente


His purchas was wel bettre an his rente


And rage he coue right as it were a whelpe /


In louedayes er coue he moche helpe /


For er he was not lich a cloysterer


With a thred bare cope as a pore scoler


But he was lik a maister or a pope


Of double worstede was his semy cope /


That rounded as a belle on the presse


Somwhat he lipsed for his wantounesse


To make his englissh sweete vpon his tonge


And in his harpyng whan at he hadde songe /


His yghen twyncled in his heed aright


As don e sterres in e frosty night


This wori lymitour was cleped huberd


A marchant was er with a forked berd


In mottle and heigh on horse he satte


Vp on his heued a Flaundrissh beuer hatte


His bootes clapsed faire and fetysly


His resons he spak ful solempnely


Schewyng alwey e encres of his wynnynge


He wolde e see were kept for eny inge


By twixe Middelburgh and Orewelle


Wel coue he in eschaunge scheldes selle /


This wory man ful wel his witte bisette


Ther wiste no wight that he was in dette


So statly was he of his gouernance


With his bargaynes and his cheuissance


For soe he was a wori man with alle


But soly to sein I not how men him calle


A Clerk er was of Oxenford also


That vnto logyk hadde long I go


As lene was his hors as is a rake


And he nas not right fat I vndertak




But loked holwe and erto soburly


Ful redbare was his ouereste courtepy


For he had geten him no benifice


Ne was so worldly for to haue office


For him was leuer to haue at his bed hede


Twenty bookes clad in blak and rede


Of Aristotle and his philosophie


Than robes riche or fithel or gay Sautrie /


But al by at he was a philosophre


it had he but alitel gold in cofre


But al at he might of his frendes hente /


On bokes and on lernyng he it / spente


And besily gan for e soules preye


Of hem at af him wher with to scoleye


Of studie took he most cure and most heede


Nought o word spak he more an was neede


And at was seyd in forme and reuerence


And schort and quyk and ful of heigh sentence


Sownyng in moral vertu was his speche


And gladly wolde he lerne and gladly teche


A Sergeant of e lawe war and wys


That often hadde ben at e Parvys


That was also / ful riche of excellence


Discret he was and of gret reuerence


He semed swich his wordes were so wise


Iustice he was ful often in assise


By patent and by plein commissioun


For his science and for his heigh renoun


Of fees and robes had he many oon


So gret a purchaceour was nowher non


Al was fee simple to him in effecte


His purchasynge might not ben infecte


No wher so besy a man as he er nas


And it he semed bisiere an he was


In termes hadde he caas and doomes alle


That from e tyme of king William were fall




Ther to he coue endite and make a ink


Ther coue no wight pynche at his writynk


And euery statut coue he plein by Rote


He rood but homly in a medly coote


Gert with a seint of silk  wi barres smale /


Of his array telle I no lenger tale


A Frankeleyn was in his compaignie


Whit was his berd as is the dayessye


Of his complexioun he was sanguyne


Wel loued he by e morwe a sop in wyne


To lyuen in delit euer was his wone /


For he was Opiournes owne sone


That held opinioun at plein delite


Was verrey felicite parfite


An houshalder and at a gret was he


Seint Iulian he was in his contre


His breed his ale was alweys after oon


A better envyned man was neuer noon


Wioute bake mete was neuer his hous


Of fissh and fleissh and at so plenteuous


It snewed in his hous of mete and drink


Of alle deyntes at men coude ink


After e sondry sesons of e ere


So changed he his mete and his sopeere


Ful many a fat partrich hadde he in Mewe


And many a brem and many a luce in stuwe


Wo was his cooke but his sauce were


Poynant and scharp and redy alle his gere


His table dormant in his halle alway


Stod redy couered alle the longe day


At Sessions er was he lord and sire


Ful ofte tyme he was knight of e schire


An anelas and a gisper al of silke


Heng at his girdel whit as morne mylke


A scherref had he ben and a comptour


Was nowher such a wori vanasou




An haburdaissher and a Carpenter


A Webbe a Dyer and a Tapecer


And ei were cloed alle in oo liuere


Of a solempne and a gret Fraternite


Ful freissch and newe here gere apiked was


Here knyfes nere chaped nought wi bras


But all wi siluer wrought ful clene and wel


Here gerdles and here pouches eueridel


Wel semed ech of hem a fair burgeys


To sitten in a yeldehalle on a deys


Euerich for e wisdom at he can


Was schaply for to ben an Alderman


For Catell hadde ei ynough and rente


And eek here wyues wolde it wel assente


And elles certein ei were to blame


It is ful fair to be cleped ma dame


And gon to vigilies al bifore


And haue a mantel rialliche / bore


A Cook ei hadde wi hem for e nones


To boyle e chikenes with e maryebones


And poudre marchannt tart and gallyngale


Wel kowde he know a draught of london ale /


He coue rost and see and broile and frie


Maken mortreux and wel bake a pye


But gret harm was it as it oughte me


That on his schyne a mormal hadde he


For blank manger at made he wi e beste /


A schipman was er wonyng fer by weste


For ought I wot he was of Dertemouthe


He rood vpon a rouncy as he coue


In a gowne of faldyng to e knee /


A dagger hangyng in a lace hadde he /


Aboute his nekke vnder his arm a doun


The hoote somer had mad his hiew al broun


And certeinly he was a good felawe


Ful many a draught of wyn he hadde draw




From Burdeaux warde whil e chapmen sleepe


Of nyce conscience took he no keepe


If at he faught and had e heigher honde


By water he sent hem hom to euery londe


But of his craft to riken wel his tydes


His stremes and his daunger him besydes


His herberwe and his moone and his ledmannage


Ther nae non such from hulle to kartage


Hardy he was and wys to vndurtake


With many a tempest had his berd be schake


He knew alle e hauenes as they were


Fro Gotlond to e Cape de fynystere


And euery Cryke in Bretaigne and in Spaigne


His barge y cleped was e Mawdeleyne


With vs er was a Doctour of Phisike


In al is world ne was er non him like


To speke of Phisik and of Surgerie


For he was grounded in astronomie


He kept his pacient a ful gret del


In houres by his magique naturel


Wel coue he fortune the ascendent


Of his ymages for his pacient


He knewe e cause of euery maladie /


Were it of hoot of cold or moist or drie /


And wher engendred and of what humour


He was a verray parfit practisour


The cause I knowe and of his harm e rote /


Anon he af e sike man his bote


Ful redy had he his appotecaries


To sende hem drugges and his letuaries


For ech of hem made oer for to wynne


Here frendschip nas nat / newe for to gynne /


Wel knew he e olde Escalapius


And discorides and eke Rusus


Olde ypocras haly and Galien


Serapion Razie and auyzen




Auerois damascien and Constantine


Bernard and Gatisdene and Gilbertine


Of his diete mesurable was he


For it was of no superfluite


But of gret norisshing and digestible


His studie was but litel on the Bible


In sangweyn and in pers he clad was al


Lyned wi Taffata and with Sendal


And yet he was but esy of dispense


He kepte at he wan in Pestilence


For gold in phisique is accordial


Therfore he loued gold in special


A good wif er was of by-syde bathe


But sche was somdel def and at was skae


Of clo makyng sche hadde such an haunte


Sche passed hem of ypres and of Gaunte


In al e parissche wif ne was er noon


at to e offryng toforn hire schulde gon


And if er dede certein wro was sche


That sche was oute of alle charite /


Hire couerchiefs ful fyne were of grounde


I dorste swere ei weyeden ten pounde


That on a soneday weren vpon hir hede


Hire hosen weren of fyn scarlet reede


Ful streyt yteyed and schoos ful moyste and newe


Bolde was hir face and fair and reed of hewe


Sche was a wori womman al hir lyue


Housbondes atte chirche dore sche hadde fyue


Wiouten oer companye in oue


But er of neede nought to speke as noue


And ries hadde sche ben at IerlmIerusalem


Sche hadde passed many a strange strem


At Rome sche hadde ben and at Boloigne


In Galice at saint Iame and at Coloigne


Sche coue moche on wandring by e weye


Gat toed was sche soly for to seye




Vpon an ambler esely sche satte


I wympled wel and on hir heed an hatte


As brood as is a bokeler or a targe


A fote mantell abouten hir hipes large /


And on hire feet a paire of spores scharpe


In felaschipe wel coue sche laughe and carpe


Of remedies of loue sche knew par chaunce /


For sche coue of at art e colde daunce


A good man was er of religioun


And was a poure persoun of a toun


But riche he was of holy ought and werk


He was also a lerned man and a clerk


That cristes gospell trewly wolde preche


His parisshiens deuoutly wolde he teche


Benigne he was and wonder diligent


And in aduersite ful pacient


and swich he was preued ofte sies


Ful lo were him to cursen for his tyes /


But raer wolde he yeuen out of doute


Vnto his poure parisshens aboute


Of his offryng and of his substance


He coue in litel ing haue suffisance


Wyd was his parisshe and houses fer a sondre


But he ne lefte nought for rayn ne ondre


In seknesse nor in meschief to visite


The ferreste in his parisshe moche and lite


Vpon his feet and in his hond a staf


This noble ensample to his scheep he yaf


That ferst he wrought and aftirward he taughte


Out of e gospel he o wordes caughte


And is fugure he addede eek / er to


That if gold ruste what schal Iren do


For if a prest be foul on whom we truste


No wonder is a lewed man to Ruste


And schame it is if a prest take kepe


A schiten schepperde and a clene schepe




Wel ought a prest ensample for to yue


By his clennes how at his scheep schulde lyue


He sette nought his benefice to hire


And leet his scheep acombred in e myre


And ran to londoun vnto Seinte Poules


To seeke him a Chaunterie for soules


Or with a breerede for to be with holde /


But duelte at hom and kepte wel his folde


So at e wolf ne made it not miscarie


He was a schepperde and not a mercenarie


And ough he holy were and vertuous


He was nought to synful men dispitous


Ne of his speche daungerous ne digne


But in his teching discret and benigne


To drawe folk to heuen by fairnesse


By good ensample is was his bisynesse /


But it were ony persone obstinat


What so he were of heigh or low estat


Him wolde he snebbe scharply for e nones


A bettre prest I trowe at nowher non es


He waited after no pompe and reuerence


Ne maked him a spiced conscience


But cristes lore and his apostles twelue


He taught but ferst he folwed in himselue /


With him er was a plowman was his broer


That hadde I ladde of dong ful many a foer


A trewe swynker and a good was he


Lyuyng in pees and parfit charite


God loued he best wi alle his herte


At alle tymes ough him gamed or smerte


And an his Neighebore right as him selue


He wolde ressche and erto dike and delue


For cristes sake for euery pouere wight


Wiouten hire if it lay in his might


His ties payed he ful fair and well


Boe of his propre swynk and his catell




In a Tabbard he rood vpon a mere


Ther was also a Reeue and a Mellere /


A Sompnour and a Pardoner also


A Maunciple and my self er nare no mo /


The meller was a stout carl for e nones


Ful big he was of brawn and eek of bones


That proued wel for ouer al ar he cam


Atte wrastlyng he wold haue a wey e ram


He was schort schuldred a ikke knarre


The was no dore at he nolde heue of harre


Or breke it at a rennyng with his heede


His berd as eny sowe or eny fox was reede


And erto brod as ough it were a spade /


Vpon e cop right of his nose he hade


A wert and er on stood a tuft of heeres


Reed as the berstles of a sowes Eres /


Hise nose rilles blake weren and wide


A swerd and bokeler bar he by his syde


His mou as gret was as a gret fourneys


He was a Iangler and a goliardeys


And at was most of synne and harlotries


Wel coue he stele corn and tolle ries


And it he hadde a ombe of gold parde


A whit cote and a blew hood wered he


A Baggepipe wel coue he blowe and soun


And er with al he brought vs out of toun


A gentil maunciple was er of a temple /


Of which achatours mighte take exsemple /


For to ben wyse in byeng of vitaile


For wheer at he paied or took by taile


Algate he wayted so in his achate


That he was ay biforn and in good estate /


Now is not at of god a ful fair grace


That such a lewed mannes witt schal pace


The wisdom of an heep of lernede men


Of maistres hadde mo an ries ten




That were of lawe expert and curious


Of which er was a dosein in that hous


Wori to ben Stywardes of Rente and londe


Of any lord at is in Ingelonde


To make him lyue by his propre good


In honour detteles but if at he were wood


Or lyue as skarsly as him list desire


And able for to helpen al a schire


In any cas at mighte falle or happe


And it is manciple sette here aler cappe


The Reeue was a sclender colerik man


His berd was schaue as nygh as euer he can


His her was by his eeres ful round y schorn


His toppe was dokked lik a prest biforn


Ful longe were his legges and ful lene


I lik a staf er was no calf y sene


Wel coue he kepe a garner or a bynne


Ther was non auditour coue on him wynne


Wel wist he by e drought and by e reyne


The yeldyng of his seed and of his greyne


His lordes scheep his neet his dayerie


His swyn his hors his stoor and his pulletrie


Was holly in is Reeues gouernynge /


And by his couenant af e rikenynge


Syn at his lord was twenty eer of age


Ther coue no man brynge him in arrerage


Ther nas baillif ne herde nor oer hyne


That he ne knew his sleight and his covyne


They were adrad of him as of e de


His wonyng was ful fair vpon an he


Wi greene trees schadewed was his place


He coue bettre an his lord purchace


Ful Riche he was astored priuely


His lord he coue plese wel subtily


To yiue and lene him of his oughne good


And haue a ank and yet a cote and hood




In oue he hadde lerned a good mester


He was a wel good wrighte a Carpenter


This reeue satte vpon a ful good stot


That was al pomely grey and highte scot


A long Surcote of pers vpon he hadde


And by his syde he bar a rusty bladde


Of Northfolk was is Reue of which I telle


Bysyden a toun men clepen it Baldeswelle


Tukked he was as is a frere aboute


And euer he rood e hyndrest of oure route


A Somynour was er with vs in at place


That hadde a fyri cherubynnes face


For Sauseflem he was with eyghen narwe /


Als hoot he was and leccherous as a sparwe


Wi scalled browes blak and piled berde /


Of his visage children weren afferde


Ther nas quyk siluer litarge or bremston


Boras orsure ne oyle of Tarte noon


Ne oynement at wolde clense and byte


To him might helpe of his whelkes white


Nor of e knobbes sittyng in his cheekes


Wel loued he garlik oynons and eek leekes


And for to drinke strong wyn reed as blood


Than wolde he speke and crye as he were wood


And whan at he wel dronken hadde e wyn


Than wold he speke no word but latyne


A fewe termes hadde he tuo or re


That he had lerned out of som decre


No wonder is he herd it al e day


And eek e knowen it wel how at a Iay


Can clepe watte as wel as can e pope


But who so coue in oer ing him grope


Than hadde he spent al his philosophie


Ay questio quid Iuris wolde he crye


He was a gentil harlot and a kynde


A bettre felaw schulde men not fynde




He wolde suffre for a quart of wyn


A good felawe to haue his concubyn


A twelf moneth and excuse him atte fulle /


Ful priuely eek a fynch coue he pulle /


And if he fond owher a good felawe


He wolde techen him to han non awe


In such caas of e Erchedeknes curs


But if mannes soule were in his purs


For in his purs he scholde punyssched be


Purs is e Erchedeknes helle seide he


But wel I wot he lyhede right in dede


Of cursyng ought eche gilty man him drede


For curs wil sle right as assoyling sauith


And also war him of a Significauith


In daunger hadde he at his owne gyse


The yonge gerles of e diocise


And knew here counseil and what was al here rede


A garland hadde he sette vpon his heede


As gret as it were for an ale stake


A bokeler hadde he made him of a cake /


With him er rood a gentill pardoner


Of Rouncyuall his frend and his comper


That streight was comen fro e court of Rome


Ful lowe he song come hider loue tome


This Somnour bar to him a stif burdoun


Was neuer trompe of half so gret a soun


This pardoner hadde her as yelow as wax


But smothe it heng as doth a strik of flax.


By ounces heng his lokkes at he hadde /


And er with he his schuldres ouer spradde


But inne it lay by culpouns on and oon


But hood for Iolite werede he noon


For it was trussed vp in his walet


Him oughte he rood al of the newe get


Discheuele saf his cappe he rood al bare


Swich glaryng yghen hadde he as an har




A vernicle hadde he sewid on his cappe


His walet biforn him in his lappe /


Bret ful of pardoun comen fro Rome al hoot


A voys he hadde as smal as a goot


No berd ne hadde he ne neuer schulde haue


As smothe it was as it ware late schaue


I trowe he were a geldyng or a mare


But of his craft fro Berwik in to ware


Ne was er such anoer pardoner


For in his male he hadde a pilewber


Which at he sayde was oure lady veyle


He seide he hadde a gobet of e seyle


That seint petir hadde whan at he wente


Vpon e see til iuihesu crist him hente


He hadde a Croys of latoun ful of stones


And in a glas he hadde pigges boones


But with ese reliqes whan at he fonde


A poure person dwellyng vpon londe /


Vpon a day he gat him more moneye


Than at e person gat in mones tweye


And us with feyned flatering and Iapes


He made e person and e poeple his apes


But trewely to tellen atte e laste


He was in chirche a noble ecclesiaste


Wel coue he rede a lessonn or a story


But aler best he song an offertory


For wel he wiste whan at song was songe


He moste preche and welaffile his tonge


To wynne seluer as he wel cowde


Ther fore he song so meriely and lowde /


Now haue I told ow soly in a clause


The estat . the array e nombre and eeke e cause


Whi at assembled was is companie


In Suthwerk at is gentil hostelrie /


That highte e Tabbard faste by e belle


But now is tyme to yow for to telle 




How at we beeren vs at ilke night


Whan we were in at Osterie alight


And after wol I telle of oure viage


And all e remenant of our pilgrimage


But ferst I pray ow of your curtesie


The e ne rette it nought my vilenye


Though at I pleinly speke in is matere


To telle ow here wordes and here cheere


Ne ough I speke here wordes propurly


For is e knowen as wel as I


Who so schal telle a tale after a man


He mot reherse as neyh as euer he can


Euerich a word if it be in his charge


Al speke he neuer so rudely and large


Or elles he moot telle his tale vntrewe


Or feyne inges or fynde wordes newe


He may nought spare al ough he were his broer


He moot als wel seie o word as anoer


Crist spak himself ful brode in holy writte


And wel e wot no vilenye is itte


Ek Plato seith who so can him rede


The wordes mot be cosyn to e dede


Also I preye ow foriue it me


Al haue I not set folk in here degre


Heer in is tale as at ei scholden stonde


My witt is schort e may wel vnderstonde


Gret cheere maad our ost vs euerychon 


And to e souper sette he vs anon


He serued vs with vitailles atte beste


Strong was e wyn and wel drynken vs leste


A semly man our hoste he was with alle


For to ben a marchall in an hall


A large man he was with eyen stepe


A fairer burgeys is er non in Chepe


Bold of his speche and wys and wel y taught


And of manhode him lakkede right naugh




Ek er to he was right a merie man


And after soper pleyen he bigan


And spak of mere amonges oer inges


Whan at he hadde maad our rikenynges


And seide us Now lordynges trewely


e ben to me welcome right hertely


For by my trouthe if at I schal not lye


I seyh not is yer so mery a companye


At oones in is herberw as is now


Fayn wold I don ou merthe wist I how


And of a mere I am right now biought


To don you eese and it schal coste nought


Ye gon to Canturbury god yow speede


The blisful martir quyte ou our meede


And wel I woot as e gon by e weye


Ye schapen ou to talen and to pleye


For trewely confort ne mere is non


To riden by e wey domb as a ston


And er for wol I make you disport


As I seide erst and do you som confort


And if ou like all by on assent


For to stonden at my Iuggement


And for to werken as I schal ou seie


To morwe whan e riden by e weie 


Now by my fader soule at is deed


But e be merye I wil eue yow myn heed


Hold vp our hond wioute more speche 


Our counseil was not longe for to seche 


Vs ought it was not wor to make it wys


And graunted him wioute more abys


And bad him seye his verdit as him leste


Lordynges quod he / now herkne for e beste


But take it nought I prey ow in disdeigne


This is e poynt to speke schort and pleigne


That ech of ou to schorte with our weye


In is viage schal telle tales twei




To Canturbury ward I mene it so


And homward he schal tellen oer tuo


Of auentures at whilom haue bifall


And which of yow at beri him best of all


That is to sein that telle in is cas


Tales of best sentence and most solas 


Schal haue a souper at our aler cost


Her in is place sittynge by is post


Whan at we comen aein fro Canturbury


And for to make ou e more mury


I wil my seluen goodly with ou ryde


Right at myn owne cost and be our gyde


And who so wol my Iuggement wi seye


Schal paye al at we spende by e weye


And if e vouche saf at it be so


Tel me anon wiouten wordes moo


And I wol erly schape me er fore


This ing was graunted and our oes swore


With ful glad herte and preyen him also


That he wolde vouche saf for to do so


And at he wolde ben our gouernour


And of oure tales Iugge and reportour


And sette a souper at a certein pris


And we wiln rewled ben at his deuys 


In heighe and lowe and us by oon assent


We ben accorded to e Iuggement


And er vpon e wyn was fet anon


We dronken and to reste went echon


Wiouten eny lenger taryyng


A morwe whan e day bigan to spryng


Vp ros oure oost and was our aler cok


And gadered vs to gider in a flok


And for we riden a litel more an paas


Vnto e wateryng of seint Thoms


And er our oost gan his hors areste


And seide lordes herkne if you lest




e wot our forward and I it ou recorde


If euynsong and morwesong acorde


Lat see now who schal telle e firste tale


As euer mote I drynke wyn of ale


Who so be rebel to my Iuggement


Schal paie for all at by e weie is spent


Now drawe Cut or at we ferer twynne


He which at ha e schortest schal bigynne


 Sir knight qdquod he my maister and my lord


Now drawe Cut for at is myn acord


Come nerre quod he my lady prioresse


And e sir clerk let be our schamfastnesse


Ne studie nought lay hond to euery man


Anon to drawe euery wight bygan


And schortly for to tellen as it was


Were it by auenture or sort ort cas


The so is is e Cut fel to e knight


Of which ful blie and glad was euery wight


And telle he moste his tale as it was resoun


By forward and by composicioun


As e han herd what nede wordes mo


And whan is good man saugh at it was so


As he at wys was and obedient


To keepe his forward by his free assent


He seide sie I schal begynne e game


What welcome be e Cutte a goddes name


Now lat vs ride and herkne what I seye


And with at word we riden for oure weye


And he bigan with right a merye cheere


His tale anon and seyde as e may heere
